athletes.Name: Shea Pitts
athletes.Biography: I’m Shea Pitts and I’m a Senior Defensive back at UCLA. I believe throughout my time at UCLA I have excelled on the field, in the community, and in the classroom. I have already completed my bachelors and masters degree within a 4 year span all while maintaining a 3.7 GPA. This led me to being elected to the Pac 12 All academic team from 2018-2021. I was also nominated as a William V. Campbell trophy finalist two years in a row which recognizes the college football player with the biggest impact in the classroom, on the field, and in the community. Recently, have been admitted into the UCLA School of Law where I will be pursuing my 3rd degree while I complete my last year of college eligibility. In terms of football, I come from a football legacy where my Grandpa played for the Packers under Vince Lombardi and won 2 Super Bowls. My Dad also played for the Packers. I am hoping to continue having an impact on the field, in the classroom, and in the community while pursing my NFL goals.

athletes.Biography: Hello, my name is Gary Moore Jr. and I am in incoming freshman at Baylor University! As someone who has had their life shaped by track, I think it’s extremely important to give back to the community and help bring up the next generation of great track athletes! I love to inspire anyone I can and help out at different events in my community ranging from coaching kids, handing out free food downtown, or just handing out water at our annual Labor Day Road Race. It brings me so much joy to see that I have accomplished one of my biggest personal goals which is to inspire those in my community and anyone I come in contact with. Theres a little pressure that comes with the territory, but it’s never too much to handle and I’ve begun to welcome it! After college, my goal is to use my degree to have my dream job of physical therapist

athletes.Name: Valentina Vivas Castañeda
athletes.Biography: My name is Valentina Vivas Castañeda, I am the goalie for Fresno State Univeristy. I was born and raised in Bogotá, Colombia and came to the U.S after playing with my national team back home, to get my BA. I played South American games and won bronze medal (were qualifier for the World Cup 2019), won medal in Cochabamba games in Bolivia and finally won gold in the bolivarianos’s game in Santa Marta. I am majoring in psychology and criminology, minoring in German with a 3.8 GPA. I want to work with a non profit that helps kids around the world. I want to use my psychology major and the experience of being an athlete to change the destiny of many kids without access to education. For instance, back home I was able to be involved with various volunteer programs that used soccer a way to bring kids out of poverty. I believe that as an athlete I get to impact so many lives that look up to me, so I live every day thinking I could inspire someone.

athletes.Biography: In high school I didn’t play much I averaged .5 points my senior year but i always stayed in the gym being undersized. I got cleared last April in 2021. I worked harder then ever and decided to transfer to a JUCO in August of 2021 which is late to transfer and take a leap of faith. I bet on myself because I knew I had got better I had also grown from 6’4 to 6’9. I played the JUCO season averaged 13pts ,6 rbs, and 3asts and earned 2 division 1 offers. I knew I had the potential to play at a higher level of basketball so I took a risk again and played in an Unsigned JUCO showcase after this showcase I was the best player in the camp and was getting interest and offers from high and mid major schools. What I had worked for my whole life payed off! UTC MBB

I have chronic long disease, asthma, and was born 16 weeks premature. I was born at 2 lbs 5 ounces. - - I have over 5000 people on Snapchat and have thousands of followers on both instagram and Twitter.- - I’ve traveled across the United States.- - I broke my left leg and dislocated my ankle in the spring season of 2021 and had to have 2 surgeries 10 months apart. I also have a rope around my ankle and 9 screws. - - I am finally back to play as a fifth year senior with a few years of eligibility to finally play the game I’ve always loved.- - I hope this can be inspirational to someone who has battled injuries and has had hardships stopping them from playing their respected sport.- View more...

athletes.Name: Margaret Mann
athletes.Biography: My name is Margaret Mann, and I am currently a wrestler on the Women’s Wrestling team at Siena Heights University.  My wrestling journey began in eighth grade when I was the statistician for the team.  My sophomore year of high school, I decided to join the school team as the first ever girl wrestler on an all male team.  I have made two appearances in the OHSAA State Women’s Wrestling Tournament.  My senior year, I placed second in the District tournament and seventh in the State tournament.  I became known as the girl who went from “Stat to States.”  Wrestling helped me grow in character and as a leader.  It has helped me through adversities such as my hearing loss.  I have mild to severe hearing loss in both ears and wear bilateral hearing aids.   I am involved in my community by participating in National Honor Society, Marching Band, Track and Field Team, 4-H and much more.  I plan to continue to grow and support my community through advocacy for people with hearing disabilities.

athletes.Name: Derell Bedingfield
athletes.Biography: I am an 18 year old from Cleveland, Ohio. I am the oldest out of 5 and I pride myself in being the best example for them. I started playing football when I was 6 years old, winning multiple city championships for the CMHA Renegades. Going on to play for and graduate from the most prestigious high school in Cleveland, Benedictine. Earning multiple All State honors in my time there led me to earning 13 division 1 offers and deciding to continue my academic and athletic career at The University of Toledo. Family and loyalty are core values to me and in choosing Toledo I kept that in mind. This journey that I am on is going to be far from easy, keeping my faith in God and always remembering my “why” there is no doubt in my mind I will succeed in anything I am apart of. My why, is not just my family. It’s to end generations of poverty in my bloodline. It’s for all the kids in Cleveland who grew up similar to me to know there is a world outside of Cleveland, Ohio. I am the one to prove it !

athletes.Biography: Hi! My name is Jackie Ghent. I am currently a college senior at Campbellsville University where I compete on the women’s wrestling team and where I will receive a degree in Business Administration with an emphasis in Human Resource Management. In anything I do, the two roles I always walk out are being 1) a Christian and 2) a leader. I am grateful to be a Christian athlete and have wrestling endeavors past the collegiate level. I am looking to make the national team, a world team and even a run for an Olympic team spot. After wrestling, I still see myself competing somehow in something new. Aside from athletics, I have a strong passion for leadership. I love coaching, mentoring, and pastoring people—areas where I can empower & encourage. I aspire for a career where I can make impact on peoples’ lives on an interpersonal level, whether that means full-time ministry or coaching. Other important topics to me are mental health awareness, eating disorders in athletes, and health & fitness.

athletes.Name: Jordan Porto
athletes.Biography: My story starts back in high school when my two older brothers were in a bad car accident. I spent all day at the hospital with them in which I had an important flag football game. I didn’t want to play in it so I could be by my brothers side but coaches, family members, and friends convinced me to play. I walked on the field and dedicated the game to my brothers who were fighting for their lives. It ended up being the best game I have ever played. I remeber running off the field to call my mom and when she answered she told me that one of them passed away during my game. I dropped to my knees as my face filled with tears. I ended up quitting the game I love. I ended up falling into a deep depression. A few years later, I was missing him and decided to step back on the field when Coach Grayson caught a glimpse of me practicing again. She decided to give me the opportunity to play the sport I grew up around and turned me into a better person. I want to inspire others to beat the odds.

athletes.Biography: My name is Connor Odom. I am a junior on the Men’s basketball team at Utah State. My father is also the head coach of the team. Basketball runs in my family. athletes.Name: Kristen Hammond
athletes.Biography: I never rowed before coming to Ohio state. I was a swimmer with a torn acl who could not compete my senior year of high school. But, I have always had a passion for sports so I decided to accept a position on the women’s rowing team at Ohio state. But being an athlete at The Ohio State university but being an athlete does not define who I am. I am from Cincinnati, Ohio and my hometown is a big part of who I am. In high school, I was voted class clown and I will never let that go. With goofiness comes responsibility, so I am constantly working whether it is volunteering or studying to keep up my grades so I can make deans list like how I did my first semester of my freshman year of college. While rowing is not a super well known sport, I am a female athlete who has sacrificed so much to be able to get better and better. I want to inspire girl athletes in my hometown and across the country.
